diff:1612370098:1612370098:=1,43d0%0a%3c :Category: PracticeCategory%0a%3c :Title: 'The original language'%0a%3c :Author: JacobF%0a%3c :Section: %0a%3c :Completed: 03.02.2021 - 08:34%0a%3c :Status: ungraded%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#history]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#historyend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c %25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#comments]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#commentsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c !!%0a%3c %0a%3c Summary: \\%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summary]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Was there some original, universal human language?%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summaryends]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Many cultures have myths or traditions concerning the origin of language, or why people speak different languages, the Tower of Babel story being a good example.%0a%3c %0a%3c However, there has also been real study into the potential of some universal 'original language' that all people spoke before eventually splitting into the languages we speak today.%0a%3c %0a%3c What are everyone's thoughts on this? Do the instructor/TAs have an opinion? Personally, I'm willing to bet that humanity had migrated enough around the time languages began to develop to allow for the possibility of multiple 'original languages' with no predecessor, but this is purely my intuitive conjecture. Any real analysis would need to pin down (relatively) very accurate estimates both for the genesis of language as well as the beginning of the world migration of the human race. It is my understanding that the incredible difficulty of either task is why the question of some old universal language is usually left alone in favor of more reasonable pursuits, i.e. trying to reconstruct PIE.%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
